english:
  title: A Question to the Creator of All Things
  author: Lee Kyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I posed a question to the Creator of All Things: "When Heaven brought forth mankind, it also brought forth the five grains so that people might eat, and then hemp and mulberry so that people might clothe themselves. By this reckoning, Heaven seems to love humanity and wish for its flourishing. Yet why does it also bring forth poisonous things? Great beasts like bears, tigers, wolves, and jackals; small creatures like mosquitoes, gadflies, fleas, and lice—these torment us grievously. By this reasoning, Heaven seems to despise humanity and wish for its destruction. How can Heaven's hatred and love be so inconstant?"

    The Creator replied: "What you ask concerns the arising of people and things—all is determined in the hidden reaches of fate and flows from what is natural. Heaven does not know this, nor does the Creator. People are born of their own accord; Heaven does not make them be born. The five grains, hemp, and mulberry come forth of themselves; Heaven does not make them come forth. How much less would there be deliberate distinction between benefit and harm placed between them? Only the person of the Way—when benefit arrives, receives it without empty joy; when poison comes, meets it without empty dread. Encountering things as though encountering emptiness, things likewise cannot harm them."

    I asked again: "When the primordial breath first divided, creating Heaven above and Earth below, with humanity between them—these are called the Three Realms. Since the Three Realms share one principle, does Heaven too contain such poisonous things?"

    The Creator answered: "Did I not just say that for the person of the Way, nothing can harm them? How could Heaven, being less accomplished than one of the Way, possess such things?"

    I said: "If that is so, then by attaining the Way, does one truly reach the Jade Capital of the Three Heavens?"

    The Creator said: "Yes."

    I replied: "My doubts are now entirely dispelled. Yet there remains one thing I do not understand. You said that Heaven does not know itself, and you do not know either. This seems fitting for Heaven, which acts through non-action and thus should not know itself. But you, the Creator—how can you not know?"

    The Creator said: "Have you seen me shape things with my hands? Things arise and transform of their own accord. What do I create? What do I know? That I am called the Creator—even this I do not understand."
  footnotes:
    - 'The ''five grains'' (五穀) refers to the staple crops of ancient East Asia: millet, rice, wheat, beans, and sesame.'
    - The 'Three Realms' (三才) is a classical cosmological concept representing Heaven, Earth, and Humanity as three interdependent aspects of existence.
    - The 'Jade Capital of the Three Heavens' (三天玉京) refers to the celestial paradise in Chinese Daoist cosmology.
    - The concept of 'the Way' (道, Tao) in this dialogue represents enlightened understanding that transcends dualistic perception of harm and benefit.
